<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-016-718  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 016 718.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Jan 3 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Microphone upgrade ships for Mac. (Apple Macintosh) (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Woods, Wendy.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Software Ventures Corp. (product introduction).andO;Product:   MicroPhone II 3.0 (Communications software) (productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Software PublishersProduct IntroductionTelecommunicationsEnhancementsMS-DOSCommunications software.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MICROPHONE UPGRADE SHIPS FOR MAC BERKELEY, CALIFORNIA, U.S.A., 1990 JAN 3(NB) -- The most popular commercial program for Macintosh telecommunications,Microphone II, now has an upgrade with a series of significant enhancements.andO;The program's success, in fact, has prompted the company to offer an MS-DOSversion in February.andM;Microphone II, from Software Ventures in Berkeley, California, now comes withsignificantly enhanced scripting power, enabling users to create their owncustom graphical interfaces based on HyperCard language and a variety oftools.andM;Says the company president, David Hindawi: &quot;We set out to break the barriersto telecommunications that many computer users experience.&quot; He adds: &quot;Peopledon't have the time or inclination to cut through the tangled interfaces ofmost remote services, so they tend to avoid telecommunications altogether.andO;Version 3.0's solution is to give users the tools -- color icons, dialogboxes, scroll boxes, and superior text editing -- to create their owncommunications interfaces.andP;  They can then replace the unfriendly interface ofany remote service with their own customized front end.&quot;andM;Public demand for the upgrade has been immense, company spokeswoman SylviaPaull tells Newsbytes.andP;  &quot;Over 1,000 have requested upgrades in the first fivedays of shipping,&quot; she says.andM;There will be a Microphone II for Windows (MS-DOS machines) coming inFebruary, she adds.andM;Software Ventures is co-owned by David Hindawi and Will Hearst, computerenthusiast and heir to the Hearst publishing empire.andM;(Wendy Woods/19900103/Press Contact: Sylvia Paull, 415-644-3232)</TEXT></DOC>